Expense reports are a day-to-day item.

4
00:00:08,020 --> 00:00:09,020
That is Jim's now.

5
00:00:09,020 --> 00:00:11,320
I am exclusively big picture.

6
00:00:11,320 --> 00:00:12,320
Epic.

7
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:13,320
Sign this.

8
00:00:13,320 --> 00:00:14,320
Where's the please?

9
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:15,320
We're not animals.

10
00:00:15,320 --> 00:00:16,320
Sign it.

11
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:17,320
No, not without a please.

12
00:00:17,320 --> 00:00:18,320
Idiot.

13
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:21,320
I have a complaint about Jim.

14
00:00:21,320 --> 00:00:23,320
That is not big picture.

15
00:00:23,320 --> 00:00:31,320
I would like to file a huge, enormous, massive complaint about the tallest guy in our office.

16
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:33,320
I'm sorry, Jim.

17
00:00:33,320 --> 00:00:35,320
I'm sorry, Jim 125.

18
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:37,320
I'm sorry, Jim.

19
00:00:37,320 --> 00:00:39,320
I'm sorry, Jim.

20
00:00:39,320 --> 00:00:41,320
I'm sorry, Jim.

21
00:00:41,320 --> 00:00:43,320
I'm sorry, Jim.

22
00:00:43,320 --> 00:00:45,320
The tallest guy in our office.

23
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,320
Jim won't sign my expense report.

24
00:00:54,320 --> 00:00:56,320
That is not okay.

25
00:00:56,320 --> 00:00:57,320
That is a big...

26
00:00:57,320 --> 00:00:58,320
That is a day-to-day...

27
00:00:58,320 --> 00:00:59,320
No, that is huge.

28
00:00:59,320 --> 00:01:00,320
You're trying to trick me.

29
00:01:00,320 --> 00:01:01,320
This has to do with...

30
00:01:01,320 --> 00:01:03,320
Get out, get out, get out, get out.

31
00:01:05,320 --> 00:01:07,320
I'd like to lodge a complaint.

32
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:08,320
I'm sorry to hear about that.

33
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:09,320
Who is this about?

34
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:10,320
You.

35
00:01:10,320 --> 00:01:11,320
Okay.

36
00:01:11,320 --> 00:01:14,320
I know I take complaints very seriously, so...

37
00:01:14,320 --> 00:01:15,320
When did this happen?

38
00:01:15,320 --> 00:01:16,320
One minute ago.

39
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:17,320
Okay.

40
00:01:17,320 --> 00:01:19,320
And how do you feel?

41
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:20,320
Angry.

42
00:01:20,320 --> 00:01:21,320
All right. Did he hit you?

43
00:01:21,320 --> 00:01:22,320
No.

44
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:23,320
Did you cry?

45
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:24,320
No.

46
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:25,320
Did you feel like crying?

47
00:01:25,320 --> 00:01:26,320
No.

48
00:01:26,320 --> 00:01:28,320
I'm just gonna write, held back tears.

49
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:29,320
Wait, stop writing that.

50
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:30,320
That is not true.

51
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:31,320
If you stop crying, I'll stop writing it.

52
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:32,320
I'm not...

53
00:01:34,320 --> 00:01:37,320
I deserve that promotion, not Jim.

54
00:01:37,320 --> 00:01:38,320
Oh, man.

55
00:01:38,320 --> 00:01:41,320
Makes me want to put him in a triangle chokehold

56
00:01:41,320 --> 00:01:43,320
and force him down to the ground

57
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:45,320
and just keep pressing and pressing

58
00:01:45,320 --> 00:01:47,320
and then flip him over

59
00:01:47,320 --> 00:01:49,320
and then put him in a hammer lock.

60
00:01:49,320 --> 00:01:52,320
And he's gasping, he's panning for every last breath.

61
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:54,320
And the crowd is going crazy.

62
00:01:54,320 --> 00:01:56,320
And boom, I emerge victorious.

63
00:01:56,320 --> 00:01:58,320
Aha!

64
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:00,320
$18,000 and a chance at the title.

65
00:02:00,320 --> 00:02:02,320
Ooh-hah!

66
00:02:02,320 --> 00:02:04,320
I have to... Jim wants you to keep it down.

67
00:02:39,320 --> 00:02:41,320
Oh, sure.

68
00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:43,320
Things are great for Michael.

69
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:45,320
And why wouldn't they be?

70
00:02:45,320 --> 00:02:47,320
Absolutely nothing's changed for him.

71
00:02:47,320 --> 00:02:50,320
He still acts like he's the only one in charge.

72
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:53,320
But today, Jim Halpert puts his foot down.

73
00:02:54,320 --> 00:02:57,320
So that was three days ago, and it didn't take.

74
00:02:57,320 --> 00:03:00,320
But today, mark my words,

75
00:03:00,320 --> 00:03:04,320
Jim Halpert really, really puts his foot down.

76
00:03:04,320 --> 00:03:07,320
Everyone, now would be a good time to freshen up

77
00:03:07,320 --> 00:03:09,320
because I'd like everyone to meet in the conference room

78
00:03:09,320 --> 00:03:11,320
in five minutes, and I suggest that you bring a snack

79
00:03:11,320 --> 00:03:13,320
because we may be in there for a while.

80
00:03:13,320 --> 00:03:14,320
Michael. Yes.

81
00:03:14,320 --> 00:03:16,320
Can I talk to you in my office for a second?

82
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:19,320
Sure, but could I first talk to you in my office?

83
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:24,320
Can I also be a boss?

84
00:03:24,320 --> 00:03:26,320
Look, it doesn't take a genius to know that any organization

85
00:03:26,320 --> 00:03:29,320
thrives when it has two leaders.

86
00:03:29,320 --> 00:03:32,320
Go ahead, name a country that doesn't have two presidents,

87
00:03:32,320 --> 00:03:35,320
a boat that sets sail without two captains.

88
00:03:35,320 --> 00:03:38,320
Where would Catholicism be without the popes?

89
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:41,320
I have noticed that we... Welcome.

90
00:03:41,320 --> 00:03:42,320
Thank you.

91
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:45,320
I've noticed we've been having a lot of conference room meetings,

92
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:48,320
and I'm wondering if perhaps those are a bit...

93
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:49,320
Disruptive. Yes.

94
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:51,320
No, I don't think they are.

95
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:54,320
I think the meetings are very important.

96
00:03:54,320 --> 00:03:56,320
Okay, maybe we should talk specifics.

97
00:03:56,320 --> 00:03:57,320
Let's do.

98
00:03:57,320 --> 00:03:58,320
Okay.

99
00:03:58,320 --> 00:04:00,320
Yesterday, we had a meeting about planets.

100
00:04:00,320 --> 00:04:04,320
Well, to be fair, Jim, James,

101
00:04:05,320 --> 00:04:06,320
and Jimothy.

102
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:08,320
To be fair, Jimothy, the...

103
00:04:08,320 --> 00:04:09,320
That sounds weird.

104
00:04:09,320 --> 00:04:11,320
Are you okay with being called Jim?

105
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:12,320
I am.

106
00:04:12,320 --> 00:04:15,320
Jim, to be fair, the conversation wasn't about planets.

107
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:19,320
At first, we were talking about introducing a line of toilet paper,

108
00:04:19,320 --> 00:04:24,320
and what part of the human body does one use toilet paper upon?

109
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:27,320
So you draw a line from there to the other planets,

110
00:04:27,320 --> 00:04:30,320
and I think by the end, we all learned a little bit about how small we are.

111
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:32,320
Yes, I agree.

112
00:04:32,320 --> 00:04:36,320
We're a big universe, and we're all just little tiny specks of dust.

113
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:40,320
I just think that maybe they're eating large amounts of the day.

114
00:04:40,320 --> 00:04:42,320
You know what eats a large amount of the day?

115
00:04:42,320 --> 00:04:43,320
Naps.

116
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:45,320
You go to sleep, it's light out, you wake up, it's dark.

117
00:04:45,320 --> 00:04:46,320
That's the whole day.

118
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:47,320
Where did that day go?

119
00:04:47,320 --> 00:04:49,320
I have no idea.

120
00:04:49,320 --> 00:04:52,320
You mean on a weekend?

121
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:54,320
Yes.

122
00:04:54,320 --> 00:04:55,320
How about this?

123
00:04:55,320 --> 00:04:58,320
I think our goal should be we don't have meetings

124
00:04:58,320 --> 00:05:00,320
unless they're absolutely essential.

125
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:02,320
No more meetings this week.

126
00:05:02,320 --> 00:05:05,320
Really? You just agree to that?

127
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:07,320
I can be very surprising.

128
00:05:16,320 --> 00:05:18,320
Do you mind?

129
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:20,320
I'll tell you what.

130
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:22,320
You show me one of those crossword puzzles that you've finished,

131
00:05:22,320 --> 00:05:24,320
and I'll be quiet in there.

132
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,320
You guys see this new memo from Jim?

133
00:05:26,320 --> 00:05:27,320
No.

134
00:05:27,320 --> 00:05:30,320
He wants us to make 20 cold calls a day.

135
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:31,320
You sure?

136
00:05:31,320 --> 00:05:33,320
In addition to all the calls we make to our clients.

137
00:05:33,320 --> 00:05:35,320
I hate making cold calls.

138
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:37,320
It's like trying to sleep with someone you've only known for a month.

139
00:05:37,320 --> 00:05:39,320
It's impossible.

140
00:05:39,320 --> 00:05:42,320
Jim needs to remember what it's like to be a salesman.

141
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:44,320
And get a new haircut.

142
00:05:44,320 --> 00:05:46,320
Thank you. I've been saying that for years.

143
00:05:46,320 --> 00:05:48,320
You know what?

144
00:05:48,320 --> 00:05:51,320
Big Tuna is starting to stink a little.

145
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:54,320
And nobody wants to be around somebody that's stinking.

146
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:56,320
Oh, no.

147
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:00,320
What's going on?

148
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:02,320
I need to fit into my wedding dress.

149
00:06:02,320 --> 00:06:05,320
However, I'm also pregnant.

150
00:06:08,320 --> 00:06:11,320
You know, it's a myth that women have to gain more than nine pounds

151
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:13,320
in a pregnancy.

152
00:06:13,320 --> 00:06:15,320
Look at these actresses. Some of them lose weight.

153
00:06:17,320 --> 00:06:19,320
Hey, did you guys register for wedding gifts?

154
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:22,320
We did, but mostly because people expect us to.

155
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:25,320
We're also accepting other gifts.

156
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:27,320
Not on the registry.

157
00:06:29,320 --> 00:06:31,320
However much.

158
00:06:31,320 --> 00:06:34,320
It's awkward asking people for money, but we could really use it.

159
00:06:35,320 --> 00:06:38,320
Why doesn't Creighton Barrow let you register for a toaster full of cash?

160
00:06:39,320 --> 00:06:41,320
Perfect. I hate registries.

161
00:06:41,320 --> 00:06:43,320
Oh, good.

162
00:06:43,320 --> 00:06:46,320
My cousin makes the most amazing romantic birdhouse mailboxes.

163
00:06:46,320 --> 00:06:49,320
I know I shouldn't tell you, but you'll still be surprised when you see it.

164
00:06:49,320 --> 00:06:52,320
You're not registered for a birdhouse, are you?

165
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:54,320
No, we're not registered for a birdhouse.

166
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:56,320
No, we're not.

167
00:06:56,320 --> 00:06:58,320
Good. Good.

168
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:05,320
Hey, Jim.

169
00:07:05,320 --> 00:07:06,320
Hey.

170
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:10,320
I just wanted to congratulate you on your promotion.

171
00:07:10,320 --> 00:07:11,320
Oh, thanks.

172
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:12,320
Yeah.

173
00:07:14,320 --> 00:07:20,320
And also, I was wondering if you could forget what I said last week

174
00:07:20,320 --> 00:07:24,320
about the fact that I don't really do my job.

175
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:27,320
Oh, sure. Is that why you've been avoiding me?

176
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:29,320
Oh, no. I wouldn't do that.

177
00:07:30,320 --> 00:07:36,320
Oh, it was just that I was late today and I took a nap in the bathroom for a while.

178
00:07:36,320 --> 00:07:39,320
All right. I think you're going to want to stop telling me those things.

179
00:07:40,320 --> 00:07:44,320
Gotcha. I will stop telling you things.

180
00:07:46,320 --> 00:07:48,320
Delicious.

181
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:49,320
All right.

182
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:51,320
Thanks, Jim.

183
00:07:51,320 --> 00:07:52,320
No problem.

184
00:07:53,320 --> 00:07:57,320
Comparing Jim and Michael is like comparing apples and oranges.

185
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:01,320
I like apples, but I really, really don't like oranges.

186
00:08:02,320 --> 00:08:04,320
Oranges are annoying and hate me.

187
00:08:05,320 --> 00:08:08,320
When you ask Jim a question, he'll tell you an answer.

188
00:08:08,320 --> 00:08:13,320
When you ask Michael a question, he'll do an imitation of you for five minutes.

189
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:16,320
Then he'll show you three YouTube videos.

190
00:08:16,320 --> 00:08:18,320
Then he'll try to tickle you.

191
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:21,320
And if that's not enough, he'll ask you to repeat the question.

192
00:08:22,320 --> 00:08:24,320
Meanwhile, he's wandered off somewhere.

193
00:08:24,320 --> 00:08:28,320
He comes back, looks at the clock, and leaves for the rest of the day.

194
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:31,320
But he also doesn't care if you come in late.

195
00:08:32,320 --> 00:08:33,320
So I prefer Michael.

196
00:08:34,320 --> 00:08:36,320
Michael is like the fun dad.

197
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:39,320
And Jim is like the serious mom.

198
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:42,320
And little Andy is stuck in the middle.

199
00:08:42,320 --> 00:08:44,320
But he loves them both very much.

200
00:08:44,320 --> 00:08:48,320
But if he had to pick one, he would probably pick Jim.

201
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:51,320
Because Jim gives him his num nums all the time.

202
00:08:52,320 --> 00:08:54,320
Num nums are, of course, my commission checks.

203
00:08:55,320 --> 00:08:56,320
Mm-hmm.

204
00:08:57,320 --> 00:08:59,320
Okay. I thought I saw people missing.

205
00:08:59,320 --> 00:09:03,320
Yeah. Just focus grouping a product expansion idea to these folks.

206
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:04,320
Got one of each.

207
00:09:04,320 --> 00:09:07,320
Really? Hey, Stanley, what was the last thing Michael said before I came through the door?

208
00:09:07,320 --> 00:09:09,320
Stanley, you don't need to answer that.

209
00:09:09,320 --> 00:09:10,320
Stanley.

210
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:12,320
If you don't smell this, you're fired.

211
00:09:12,320 --> 00:09:15,320
Okay. Michael, I thought we agreed to not take up people's time with meetings like these.

212
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:18,320
What do you mean by these people?

213
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:20,320
Michael, this is a conference room meeting.

214
00:09:21,320 --> 00:09:26,320
Oh, hey, everybody. I think that Jim has gone insane because he thinks that my office is a conference room.

215
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:27,320
That's not what I meant.

216
00:09:27,320 --> 00:09:33,320
Listen, Jim, no offense, but when push comes to shove, what I want is more important than what you want.

217
00:09:33,320 --> 00:09:34,320
I disagree.

218
00:09:34,320 --> 00:09:35,320
What do you guys think?

219
00:09:35,320 --> 00:09:37,320
Can I go back to my desk now?

220
00:09:37,320 --> 00:09:39,320
Great. Guys, can I just have a moment alone with Michael?

221
00:09:39,320 --> 00:09:41,320
No, no, no, no. You don't need to go anywhere.

222
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:45,320
Anything that Jim has to say to me, he can say in front of these types of people.

223
00:09:45,320 --> 00:09:52,320
That is not what I said. And also, I am co-manager, meaning you are not the only manager anymore. I am also a co-manager.

224
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:53,320
That is not what Wallace told us.

225
00:09:53,320 --> 00:09:54,320
That's exactly what Wallace told us.

226
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:56,320
That is not the way I heard it.

227
00:09:57,320 --> 00:10:02,320
I love rivalries. Michael or Jim. Paris or Nicole. Heidi or Elsie. It's so much fun.

228
00:10:03,320 --> 00:10:08,320
But I guess if I'm really thinking about it and answering your question honestly, I'd have to go with Elsie.

229
00:10:08,320 --> 00:10:11,320
Heidi is a bad friend and her skin is terrible.

230
00:10:11,320 --> 00:10:17,320
It is one thing me giving you the co-manager title. It is another thing you bossing me around.

231
00:10:17,320 --> 00:10:22,320
I'm not bossing you around. I'm trying to do my job, which is sharing your job. So maybe we should just call David Wallace.

232
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:26,320
No, no, no. No, we will not call David Wallace. I will call David Wallace.

233
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:28,320
David Wallace is on line two for you guys.

234
00:10:28,320 --> 00:10:31,320
Or David Wallace will call us on line two. Why don't we just...

235
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:32,320
Hey, David.

236
00:10:32,320 --> 00:10:33,320
Hey, David.

237
00:10:33,320 --> 00:10:34,320
You got Jim here.

238
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:35,320
This is Michael, senior co-manager.

239
00:10:35,320 --> 00:10:44,320
Hey, guys. I'm calling because unfortunately we will not be able to give out cost of living raises this year.

240
00:10:44,320 --> 00:10:49,320
And I know people expect it. However, there just is only a small amount of money for each branch.

241
00:10:49,320 --> 00:10:53,320
So we're leaving it up to the managers to decide how to distribute it.

242
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:57,320
Got it, Dave. Sounds like your classic big picture decision.

243
00:10:57,320 --> 00:11:00,320
Which will clearly affect the day-to-day well-being of our employees.

244
00:11:00,320 --> 00:11:01,320
It's probably a little of both.

245
00:11:01,320 --> 00:11:02,320
Which is it more of?

246
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:03,320
Excuse me?

247
00:11:03,320 --> 00:11:07,320
Hey, David. I know that I'm very new at this, but I have a very good perspective on how things work.

248
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:11,320
Wait, I'm sorry. Michael, are you texting me?

249
00:11:11,320 --> 00:11:14,320
I thought maybe we could talk after this is over.

250
00:11:14,320 --> 00:11:18,320
Look, I need you both to take care of this. This is not going to be a problem, is it?

251
00:11:18,320 --> 00:11:19,320
Nope. Not at all.

252
00:11:19,320 --> 00:11:20,320
No, it will not be.

253
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:21,320
Nope.

254
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,320
I am on top of it.

255
00:11:22,320 --> 00:11:23,320
Alright. Thanks a lot, David.

256
00:11:23,320 --> 00:11:25,320
Talk to you later. Okay, you didn't let me...

257
00:11:25,320 --> 00:11:26,320
Say goodbye.

258
00:11:27,320 --> 00:11:30,320
Alright. I am looking forward to this.

259
00:11:30,320 --> 00:11:31,320
You don't have to lie.

260
00:11:31,320 --> 00:11:33,320
I hate the fact that we have to do this together.

261
00:11:33,320 --> 00:11:35,320
I think we work much better separately.

262
00:11:35,320 --> 00:11:40,320
When I am irritated and I look at you, I don't see you anymore.

263
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:43,320
All I can see is how big and gross the pores on your nose are.

264
00:11:43,320 --> 00:11:46,320
Alright. Let's get started.

265
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:54,320
Hey, why haven't we ever...

266
00:11:54,320 --> 00:11:56,320
We have.

267
00:11:56,320 --> 00:12:01,320
Okay, we can give everyone a tiny raise if we keep it to the 1.5%.

268
00:12:01,320 --> 00:12:05,320
Then everyone is just a little bit mad.

269
00:12:05,320 --> 00:12:09,320
Okay. Let's do it. Let's do it.

270
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:10,320
Thank you, Sean.

271
00:12:10,320 --> 00:12:14,320
Wait. On the other hand, if any of the sales staff feel underappreciated,

272
00:12:14,320 --> 00:12:17,320
one of them can leave and actually take clients with them, which would hurt everyone.

273
00:12:17,320 --> 00:12:19,320
So maybe we should give it to the sales staff.

274
00:12:19,320 --> 00:12:20,320
Want to go for a walk?

275
00:12:20,320 --> 00:12:21,320
Let's see what that looks like.

276
00:12:21,320 --> 00:12:22,320
I'll get something to eat.

277
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:23,320
No.

278
00:12:23,320 --> 00:12:24,320
Let's get some pie. You want some pie?

279
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:25,320
No.

280
00:12:25,320 --> 00:12:26,320
Pie was helping me think.

281
00:12:26,320 --> 00:12:30,320
Where could we go to get something to eat where we have to travel?

282
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:32,320
It would help us think.

283
00:12:32,320 --> 00:12:34,320
Maybe you could help come up with a solution.

284
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:35,320
Why don't we just give it to Stanley?

285
00:12:35,320 --> 00:12:36,320
Why is that?

286
00:12:36,320 --> 00:12:40,320
Because he was just looking at me and his eyes said,

287
00:12:40,320 --> 00:12:41,320
Give me the money.

288
00:12:41,320 --> 00:12:43,320
So we just do whatever comes out the top of your head?

289
00:12:43,320 --> 00:12:45,320
There are worse ways of making decisions, Jim.

290
00:12:45,320 --> 00:12:48,320
Here, Stanley, have an 80% increase for absolutely no reason.

291
00:12:48,320 --> 00:12:51,320
No reason? Wow. Racist.

292
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:52,320
Put it this way.

293
00:12:52,320 --> 00:12:55,320
Would you walk into Cooper's and order the first thing off the menu?

294
00:12:55,320 --> 00:12:57,320
I do. Coconut shrimp.

295
00:12:57,320 --> 00:12:59,320
What?

296
00:12:59,320 --> 00:13:02,320
No, just for such a big catfish fan, I thought.

297
00:13:02,320 --> 00:13:05,320
Well, Cooper's has the best New Orleans-style catfish I've ever had.

298
00:13:05,320 --> 00:13:06,320
Sides?

299
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:07,320
You can pick two.

300
00:13:07,320 --> 00:13:09,320
Damn it to hell.

301
00:13:09,320 --> 00:13:11,320
You know, there's no easy way to do this.

302
00:13:11,320 --> 00:13:14,320
I say we add 1.5% of the total.

303
00:13:14,320 --> 00:13:16,320
You know, there's no easy way to do this.

304
00:13:16,320 --> 00:13:21,320
I say we add 1.5% to their paychecks and don't say anything about it.

305
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:25,320
Do you mean like break in in the middle of the night and change the numbers on payroll?

306
00:13:25,320 --> 00:13:28,320
No, we can do it during the day. It doesn't have to be that dramatic, Jim.

307
00:13:28,320 --> 00:13:34,320
Okay. You know, what would help is a pros and cons list for our options.

308
00:13:34,320 --> 00:13:37,320
Jim, don't take this the wrong way. Are you going to take this the wrong way?

309
00:13:37,320 --> 00:13:39,320
It's hard to tell so far.

310
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:40,320
You use your brain too much.

311
00:13:40,320 --> 00:13:42,320
I'm sorry, are you advocating that I use it less?

312
00:13:42,320 --> 00:13:45,320
Sometimes the smartest people don't think at all.

313
00:13:45,320 --> 00:13:46,320
You just came up with that.

314
00:13:46,320 --> 00:13:47,320
As I was saying it.

315
00:13:47,320 --> 00:13:48,320
Yeah.

316
00:13:48,320 --> 00:13:53,320
Okay, so for the 1.5% increase, pro, everyone gets a little bit.

317
00:13:53,320 --> 00:13:55,320
Con, you look like a nerd.

318
00:13:55,320 --> 00:13:58,320
Con, no one gets as much as they did last year.

319
00:13:58,320 --> 00:14:01,320
Pro, you get to share your pros and cons list with the other nerds.

320
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:03,320
Pro, no favoritism.

321
00:14:03,320 --> 00:14:09,320
Con, you unzip your pants and you find that there's a calculator out there.

322
00:14:09,320 --> 00:14:14,320
I've been studying Michael for years and I've condensed what I've learned into this chart.

323
00:14:14,320 --> 00:14:16,320
How Michael spends his time.

324
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:19,320
As you can see, we have procrastinating and distracting others.

325
00:14:19,320 --> 00:14:23,320
And this tiny sliver here is critical thinking.

326
00:14:23,320 --> 00:14:26,320
I made it bigger so that you could see it.
